series of lectures delivered by Lonergan at Boston College in 1957 illustrates a pivotal time in Lonergan's intellectual history, marking both the transition from the faculty psychology still present in his work Insight to intentionality analysis and his initial differentiation of the existential level of consciousness. The lectures on logic deal with the general character of mathematical logic and its relation to truth, Scholasticism, and Aristotelian logic. Continuing Lonergan's long-standing interest in the foundations of thought, the lectures on existentialism offer a penetrating account of Husserl and his influence. They also deal with Jaspers, Heidegger, Sartre, and Marcel. They offer reflections on such topics as being oneself, dread, horizon, and the existential gap. Perhaps more dramatically than in any other work these papers reveal Lonergan's dual commitment to the rigor of scientific analysis (in the field of mathematical logic) and to the sensitivity of continental philosophies to existential issues.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aExistentialism. 0aLogic, Symbolic and mathematical. 0aPhenomenology. 0aTheologyy20th century. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh1 aCrowe, Frederick E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoran, Robert M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcShane, Philip, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcshane, Philip J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267839240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442678392423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442678392.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL